subpages.title: A re-introduction to JavaScript (JS Tutorial)
subpages.summary: Why a re-introduction? Because JavaScript has a reasonable claim to being the world's most misunderstood programming language. While often derided as a toy, beneath its deceptive simplicity lie some powerful language features. 2005 saw the launch of a number of high-profile JavaScript applications, showing that deeper knowledge of this technology is an important skill for any web developer.

subpages.title: About JavaScript
subpages.summary: JavaScript® is the Netscape-developed object scripting language used in millions of web pages and server applications worldwide. Netscape's JavaScript is a superset of the ECMA-262 Edition 3 (ECMAScript) standard scripting language, with only mild differences from the published standard.

subpages.title: Advancing JavaScript with Libraries (Presentation)
subpages.summary: A presentation given by Mozilla employee John Resig at Yahoo to a number of their developers. The presentation is on the importance of JavaScript Libraries, and how their introduction and use changes how JavaScript development works. He discuss some of what he's learned from developing, and working with the users of, jQuery and in developing the new FUEL library for Firefox 3.

subpages.title: Compatibility
subpages.summary: This is where the aggregated JavaScript compatibility tables will live.

subpages.title: Data structures
subpages.summary: Programming languages all have built-in data structures, but these often differ from one language to another. This article attempts to list the built-in data structures available in JavaScript and what properties they have; these can be used to build other data structures. When possible, comparisons with other languages are drawn.

subpages.title: ECMAScript 5 support in Mozilla
subpages.summary: ECMAScript 5.1, the latest edition of the standard upon which JavaScript is based, was approved in June 2011.

subpages.title: ECMAScript 6 support in Mozilla
subpages.summary: ECMAScript 6 is the next version of the standard, code-named "Harmony" or "ES.next". Specification drafts can be found on the official wiki. If you wish to send feedback about the standard, do it on es-discuss.

subpages.title: Getting Started (Javascript Tutorial)
subpages.summary: JavaScript is a powerful, complicated and not very well understood language in the field of computer languages. However, at its core potential lies the ability to develop interactive Web pages and applications, allowing users to enter data efficiently and for those Web pages and applications to present the result in a much practical way.

subpages.title: Introduction to Object-Oriented JavaScript
subpages.summary: JavaScript has strong object-oriented programming capabilities, even though some debates have taken place due to the differences in object-oriented JavaScript compared to other languages.

subpages.title: About this Guide
subpages.summary: JavaScript is a cross-platform, object-based scripting language. This guide explains everything you need to know about using JavaScript.

subpages.title: Closures
subpages.summary: Closures are often considered an advanced feature in JavaScript, but understanding them is essential to mastering the language.

subpages.title: Concurrency model and Event Loop
subpages.summary: JavaScript has a concurrency model based on an "event loop". This model is quite different than the model in other languages like C or Java.

subpages.title: Details of the object model
subpages.summary: JavaScript is an object-based language based on prototypes, rather than being class-based. Because of this different basis, it can be less apparent how JavaScript allows you to create hierarchies of objects and to have inheritance of properties and their values. This chapter attempts to clarify the situation.

subpages.title: Expressions and operators
subpages.summary: This chapter describes JavaScript expressions and operators, including assignment, comparison, arithmetic, bitwise, logical, string, and special operators.

subpages.title: Functions
subpages.summary: Functions are one of the fundamental building blocks in JavaScript. A function is a JavaScript procedure—a set of statements that performs a task or calculates a value. To use a function, you must define it somewhere in the scope from which you wish to call it.

subpages.title: Inheritance and the prototype chain
subpages.summary: JavaScript is a bit confusing for developers experienced in class-based languages (like Java or C++), as it is dynamic and does not provide a class implementation (although the keyword class is a reserved keyword and cannot be used as a variable name).

subpages.title: Regular Expressions
subpages.summary: Regular expressions are patterns used to match character combinations in strings. In JavaScript, regular expressions are also objects. These patterns are used with the exec and test methods of RegExp, and with the match, replace, search, and split methods of String. This chapter describes JavaScript regular expressions.

subpages.title: About this Reference
subpages.summary: Some programming experience with a language such as C or Visual Basic is useful, but not required.

subpages.title: Code comments
subpages.summary: Comments are used to add hints, notes, suggestions, or warnings to JavaScript code. This can make it easier to read and understand. They can also be used to disable code to prevent it from being executed; this can be a valuable debugging tool.

subpages.title: Deprecated and obsolete features
subpages.summary: This appendix lists features of JavaScript that are deprecated (that is, still available but planned for removal) and obsolete (that is, no longer usable).

subpages.title: Transitioning to strict mode
subpages.summary: ECMAScript 5 introduced strict mode which is now implemented in all major browsers (including IE10). While making web browsers interpret code as strict is easy (just add "use strict"; at the top of your source code), transitioning an existing code base to strict mode requires a bit more work.

subpages.title: arguments.callee
subpages.summary: Specifies the currently executing function.

subpages.title: arguments.length
subpages.summary: Specifies the number of arguments passed to the function.

subpages.title: caller
subpages.summary: Specifies the function that invoked the currently executing function.

subpages.title: arguments
subpages.summary: An Array-like object corresponding to the arguments passed to a function.

subpages.title: Functions and function scope
subpages.summary: Generally speaking, a function is a "subprogram" that can be called by code external (or internal in the case of recursion) to the function. Like the program itself, a function is composed of a sequence of statements called the function body. Values can be passed to a function, and the function can return a value.

subpages.title: Array every method
subpages.summary: Tests whether all elements in the array pass the test implemented by the provided function.

subpages.title: Array filter method
subpages.summary: Creates a new array with all elements that pass the test implemented by the provided function.

subpages.title: Array indexOf method
subpages.summary: Returns the first index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present.

subpages.title: Array join method
subpages.summary: Joins all elements of an array into a string.

subpages.title: Array push method
subpages.summary: Mutates an array by appending the given elements and returning the new length of the array.

subpages.title: Array reduce method
subpages.summary: Apply a function against an accumulator and each value of the array (from left-to-right) as to reduce it to a single value.

subpages.title: Array reduceRight method
subpages.summary: Apply a function simultaneously against two values of the array (from right-to-left) as to reduce it to a single value.

subpages.title: Array slice method
subpages.summary: Returns a shallow copy of a portion of an array.

subpages.title: Array some method
subpages.summary: Tests whether some element in the array passes the test implemented by the provided function.

subpages.title: Array splice method
subpages.summary: Changes the content of an array, adding new elements while removing old elements.

subpages.title: Array toSource method
subpages.summary: Returns a string representing the source code of the array.

subpages.title: Array toString method
subpages.summary: Returns a string representing the specified array and its elements.

subpages.title: Array.concat
subpages.summary: Returns a new array comprised of this array joined with other array(s) and/or value(s).

subpages.title: Array.forEach
subpages.summary: Executes a provided function once per array element.

subpages.title: Array.isArray
subpages.summary: Returns true if an object is an array, false if it is not.

subpages.title: Array.lastIndexOf
subpages.summary: Returns the last index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present. The array is searched backwards, starting at fromIndex.

subpages.title: Array.length
subpages.summary: An unsigned, 32-bit integer that specifies the number of elements in an array.

subpages.title: Array.pop
subpages.summary: Removes the last element from an array and returns that element.

subpages.title: Array.prototype
subpages.summary: Represents the prototype for the Array constructor.

subpages.title: Array.prototype.map()
subpages.summary: Creates a new array with the results of calling a provided function on every element in this array.

subpages.title: Array.reverse
subpages.summary: Reverses an array in place.  The first array element becomes the last and the last becomes the first.

subpages.title: Array.shift
subpages.summary: Removes the first element from an array and returns that element. This method changes the length of the array.

subpages.title: Array.sort
subpages.summary: Sorts the elements of an array in place and returns the array.

subpages.title: Array.unshift
subpages.summary: Adds one or more elements to the beginning of an array and returns the new length of the array.

subpages.title: constructor
subpages.summary: Returns a reference to the Array function that created the instance's prototype. Note that the value of this property is a reference to the function itself, not a string containing the function's name.

subpages.title: Array
subpages.summary: The JavaScript Array global object is a constructor for arrays, which are high-level, list-like objects.

subpages.title: Boolean.toSource
subpages.summary: Returns a string representing the source code of the object.

subpages.title: constructor
subpages.summary: Returns a reference to the Boolean function that created the instance's prototype. Note that the value of this property is a reference to the function itself, not a string containing the function's name.

subpages.title: prototype
subpages.summary: Represents the prototype for the Boolean constructor.

subpages.title: toString
subpages.summary: Returns a string representing the specified Boolean object.

subpages.title: valueOf
subpages.summary: Returns the primitive value of a Boolean object.

subpages.title: Boolean
subpages.summary: The Boolean object is an object wrapper for a boolean value.

subpages.title: Date.UTC
subpages.summary: Accepts the same parameters as the longest form of the constructor, and returns the number of milliseconds in a Date object since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00, universal time.

subpages.title: Date.getDate
subpages.summary: Returns the day of the month for the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: Date.getDay
subpages.summary: Returns the day of the week for the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: Date.getFullYear
subpages.summary: Returns the year of the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: Date.getMinutes
subpages.summary: Returns the minutes in the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: Date.getMonth
subpages.summary: Returns the month in the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: Date.getSeconds
subpages.summary: Returns the seconds in the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: Date.getTime
subpages.summary: Returns the numeric value corresponding to the time for the specified date according to universal time.

subpages.title: Date.getTimezoneOffset
subpages.summary: Returns the time-zone offset from UTC, in minutes, for the current locale.

subpages.title: Date.getUTCFullYear
subpages.summary: Returns the year in the specified date according to universal time.

subpages.title: Date.getYear
subpages.summary: Returns the year in the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: Date.now
subpages.summary: Returns the number of milliseconds elapsed since 1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC.

subpages.title: Date.parse
subpages.summary: Parses a string representation of a date, and returns the number of milliseconds since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC.

subpages.title: Date.prototype
subpages.summary: Represents the prototype for the Date constructor.

subpages.title: Date.setDate
subpages.summary: Sets the day of the month for a specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: Date.toDateString
subpages.summary: Returns the date portion of a Date object in human readable form in American English.

subpages.title: Date.toLocaleString
subpages.summary: Converts a date to a string, using the operating system's locale's conventions.

subpages.title: Date.toLocaleTimeString
subpages.summary: Converts a date to a string, returning the "time" portion using the current locale's conventions.

subpages.title: Date.toSource
subpages.summary: Returns a string representing the source code of the object.

subpages.title: Date.toString
subpages.summary: Returns a string representing the specified Date object.

subpages.title: Date.toTimeString
subpages.summary: Returns the time portion of a Date object in human readable form in American English.

subpages.title: Date.valueOf
subpages.summary: Returns the primitive value of a Date object.

subpages.title: constructor
subpages.summary: Returns a reference to the Date function that created the instance's prototype. Note that the value of this property is a reference to the function itself, not a string containing the function's name.

subpages.title: getHours
subpages.summary: Returns the hour for the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: getMilliseconds
subpages.summary: Returns the milliseconds in the specified date according to local time.

subpages.title: getUTCDate

subpages.title: Global Objects
subpages.summary: This chapter documents all the JavaScript objects, along with their methods and properties.

subpages.title: Arithmetic Operators
subpages.summary: Arithmetic operators take numerical values (either literals or variables) as their operands and return a single numerical value. The standard arithmetic operators are addition (+), subtraction (-), multiplication (*), and division (/).

subpages.title: Assignment Operators
subpages.summary: An assignment operator assigns a value to its left operand based on the value of its right operand.

subpages.title: Bitwise Operators
subpages.summary: Bitwise operators treat their operands as a sequence of 32 bits (zeros and ones), rather than as decimal, hexadecimal, or octal numbers. For example, the decimal number nine has a binary representation of 1001. Bitwise operators perform their operations on such binary representations, but they return standard JavaScript numerical values.

subpages.title: Comma Operator
subpages.summary: The comma operator evaluates both of its operands (from left to right) and returns the value of the second operand.

subpages.title: Comparison Operators
subpages.summary: JavaScript has both strict and Type–converting (abstract) comparisons. A strict comparison (e.g. ===) is only true if the operands are the same Type. The more commonly used abstract comparison (e.g. ==) converts the operands to the same Type before making the comparison. For relational abstract comparisons (e.g. <=), the operands are first converted to primitives, then the same Type, before comparison.

subpages.title: Conditional Operator
subpages.summary: The conditional operator is the only JavaScript operator that takes three operands. This operator is frequently used as a shortcut for the if statement.

subpages.title: Logical Operators
subpages.summary: Logical operators are typically used with Boolean (logical) values; when they are, they return a Boolean value. However, the && and || operators actually return the value of one of the specified operands, so if these operators are used with non-Boolean values, they may return a non-Boolean value.

subpages.title: Member Operators
subpages.summary: Member operators provide access to an object's properties and methods.

subpages.title: Operator Precedence
subpages.summary: Operator precedence determines the order in which operators are evaluated. Operators with higher precedence are evaluated first.

subpages.title: String Operators
subpages.summary: In addition to the comparison operators, which can be used on string values, the concatenation operator (+) concatenates two string values together, returning another string that is the union of the two operand strings. For example, "my " + "string" returns the string "my string".

subpages.title: delete
subpages.summary: The delete operator removes a property from an object.

subpages.title: function
subpages.summary: The function operator defines a function inside an expression.

subpages.title: get
subpages.summary: Binds an object property to a function that will be called when that property is looked up.

subpages.title: in
subpages.summary: The in operator returns true if the specified property is in the specified object.

subpages.title: instanceof
subpages.summary: The instanceof operator tests whether an object has in its prototype chain the prototype property of a constructor.

subpages.title: new
subpages.summary: The new operator creates an instance of a user-defined object type or of one of the built-in object types that has a constructor function.

subpages.title: set
subpages.summary: Binds an object property to a function to be called when there is an attempt to set that property.

subpages.title: this
subpages.summary: A function's this keyword behaves a little differently in JavaScript compared to other languages. It also has some differences between strict mode and non-strict mode.

subpages.title: typeof
subpages.summary: The typeof operator returns a string indicating the type of the unevaluated operand.

subpages.title: void
subpages.summary: The void operator evaluates the given expression and then returns undefined.

subpages.title: yield
subpages.summary: The yield keyword is used to pause and resume a generator.

subpages.title: Reserved Words
subpages.summary: The following are keywords and may not be used as variables, functions, methods, or object identifiers, because ECMAScript specifies special behavior for them:

subpages.title: Rest parameters
subpages.summary: Representation of an indefinite number of arguments as an array.

subpages.title: Scope Cheatsheet
subpages.summary: JavaScript with Mozilla extensions has both function-scoped vars and block-scoped lets. Along with hoisting and dynamic behavior, scope in JavaScript is sometimes surprising.

subpages.title: Spread operator
subpages.summary: The spread construct allows an expression to be expanded in places where multiple arguments (for function calls) or multiple elements (for array literals) are expected.

subpages.title: block
subpages.summary: A block statement is used to group zero or more statements. The block is delimited by a pair of curly brackets.

subpages.title: break
subpages.summary: Terminates the current loop, switch, or label statement and transfers program control to the statement following the terminated statement.

subpages.title: const
subpages.summary: Declares a read-only, named constant.

subpages.title: continue
subpages.summary: Terminates execution of the statements in the current iteration of the current or labelled loop, and continues execution of the loop with the next iteration.

subpages.title: debugger
subpages.summary: Invokes any available debugging functionality. If no debugging functionality is available, this statement has no effect.

subpages.title: do...while
subpages.summary: Creates a loop that executes a specified statement until the test condition evaluates to false. The condition is evaluated after executing the statement, resulting in the specified statement executing at least once.

subpages.title: export
subpages.summary: Allows a signed script to provide properties, functions, and objects to other signed or unsigned scripts. This feature is not in ECMA-262, Edition 3.

subpages.title: for
subpages.summary: Creates a loop that consists of three optional expressions, enclosed in parentheses and separated by semicolons, followed by a statement executed in the loop.

subpages.title: for each...in
subpages.summary: Iterates a specified variable over all values of object's properties. For each distinct property, a specified statement is executed.

subpages.title: for...in
subpages.summary: Iterates over the enumerable properties of an object, in arbitrary order. For each distinct property, statements can be executed.

subpages.title: for...of
subpages.summary: Iterates over iterable objects (including arrays, array-like objects, iterators and generators), invoking a custom iteration hook with statements to be executed for the value of each distinct property.

subpages.title: function
subpages.summary: Declares a function with the specified parameters.

subpages.title: if...else
subpages.summary: Executes a statement if a specified condition is true. If the condition is false, another statement can be executed.

subpages.title: import
subpages.summary: Allows a script to import properties, functions, and objects from a signed script that has exported the information. This feature is not in ECMA 262, Edition 3.

subpages.title: label
subpages.summary: Provides a statement with an identifier that you can refer to using a break or continue statement.

subpages.title: let
subpages.summary: Declares a block scope local variable, optionally initializing it to a value.

subpages.title: return
subpages.summary: Specifies the value to be returned by a function.

subpages.title: switch
subpages.summary: Evaluates an expression, matching the expression's value to a case label, and executes statements associated with that case.

subpages.title: throw
subpages.summary: Throws a user-defined exception.

subpages.title: try...catch
subpages.summary: Marks a block of statements to try, and specifies a response, should an exception be thrown.

subpages.title: var
subpages.summary: Declares a variable, optionally initializing it to a value.

subpages.title: while
subpages.summary: Creates a loop that executes a specified statement as long as the test condition evaluates to true. The condition is evaluated before executing the statement.

subpages.title: with
subpages.summary: Extends the scope chain for a statement.

subpages.title: Statements
subpages.summary: JavaScript statements consist of keywords used with the appropriate syntax. A single statement may span multiple lines. Multiple statements may occur on a single line if each statement is separated by a semicolon.

subpages.title: Symbols
subpages.summary: This page is intended to serve as a one-stop reference for symbols, allowing one to find information on the meaning and uses of various symbols that can be found in JavaScript (and for syntaxes used within JavaScript such as regular expressions and E4X/XML).

subpages.title: default parameters
subpages.summary: Allow formal parameters to be initialized with default values if no value or undefined is passed.

subpages.title: JavaScript shells
subpages.summary: A JavaScript shell allows you to quickly test snippets of JavaScript code without having to reload a web page. They are extremely useful for developing and debugging code.

subpages.title: JavaScript technologies overview
subpages.summary: While HTML is used to store the content and formatting of a web page and CSS encodes the style of how the formatted content should be graphically displayed, JavaScript is used to create rich effects or rich web applications. However, the umbrella term "JavaScript" as understood in the web browser context contains several very different elements. One of them is the core language (ECMAScript), another is the DOM (Document Object Model).

subpages.summary: In Computer science a daemon is a task that runs as a background process, rather than being under the direct control of an interactive user. In JavaScript programming language, are called daemons all processes created by JavaScript timers or by a Worker instantiation. Here are some code snippets which simplify and abstract the management of daemons.

subpages.title: ArrayBuffer
subpages.summary: The ArrayBuffer is a data type that is used to represent a generic, fixed-length binary data buffer. You can't directly manipulate the contents of an ArrayBuffer; instead, you create an ArrayBufferView object which represents the buffer in a specific format, and use that to read and write the contents of the buffer.

subpages.title: JavaScript typed arrays
subpages.summary: As web applications become more and more powerful, adding features such as audio and video manipulation, access to raw data using WebSockets, and so forth, it has become clear that there are times when it would be helpful for JavaScript code to be able to quickly and easily manipulate raw binary data. In the past, this had to be simulated by treating the raw data as a string and using the charCodeAt() method to read the bytes from the data buffer.

subpages.title: Memory Management
subpages.summary: Low-level languages, like C, have low-level memory management primitives like malloc() and free(). On the other hand, JavaScript values are allocated when things (objects, strings, etc.) are created and "automatically" free'd when they are not used anymore. The latter process is called garbage collection. This "automatically" is a source of confusion and gives JavaScript (and high-level languages) developers the impression they can decide not to care about memory management. This is a mistake.

subpages.title: Sharp variables in JavaScript
subpages.summary: A sharp variable is a syntax in object initializers that allows serialization of objects that have cyclic references or multiple references to the same object.

title: JavaScript
summary: JavaScript® (often shortened to JS) is a lightweight, interpreted, object-oriented language with first-class functions, most known as the scripting language for Web pages, but used in many non-browser environments as well such as node.js or Apache CouchDB.
